english:
  title: Another Letter
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to you now. Since ancient times, many who have failed the examinations have found themselves buried in obscurity. Yet my own case presents something I cannot quite fathom. I sat for the civil service twice, and twice I was rejected. Later, beset by troubles, I drifted along until now—barely three attempts, and my beard has turned nearly white. Then illness struck me down. It seems the distant heavens have willed it so. This is what Xiang Yu meant when he said, "Heaven destroys me; it is not the fault of my warfare." I have long believed that Heaven's punishment falls so heavily upon me because my name exceeds my substance. For a name is a public trust—one cannot seize it arbitrarily. Su Zhe spoke truly when he said that to receive high reward without merit is as culpable as taking an ill-gotten name. Indeed, these are honest words. I do not wish for men like you to heap praise upon me and thereby deepen my transgression. What benefit could come from grasping at empty fame and inviting real calamity?

    Alas, I am utterly useless. In my heart, I compare myself to the minor clerks and soldiers of a well-ordered age, yet I cannot even attain such a station. If I were to liken myself to the common folk, no one matches my wretchedness. I have gladly consigned myself to waste and abandoned all hope of displaying my meager talents to the world.

    You possess great talent and have encountered a enlightened age—surely you will accomplish something of note. The decline of letters has never been so severe as in these times. If you and two or three others like you will sing out in harmony and restore its glory, what glory your efforts shall bring! There is so much I wish to say to you, yet paper fails and brush grows worn. I can only write this incomplete letter. I remain, respectfully yours.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Xiang Yu: The famous warlord of the Chu-Han contention period, said to have believed Heaven itself had turned against him before his defeat.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Su Zhe (蘇子瞻): Alternative name for Su Shi, the great Song dynasty poet and statesman, known for his moral wisdom.'
  - key: ''
    value: The repeated failures at the examinations were a common source of anguish for educated men in East Asia, and became a frequent theme in their correspondence and literary works.
